{"summary":"Current tree already resolves the journal-detail struct deduplication, but the plan_hash changes split into two different cases. Removing snapshot-based defaulting for newly created running rows is a real regression: it contradicts the accepted contract, drops plan lineage from fresh start rows and start journal events, and the deferred backfill logic does not actually eliminate the claimed race because it later trusts the same creation snapshot anyway. By contrast, skipping backfill for legacy rows with no provenance is a sound safety guard; those rows are genuinely ambiguous, and blindly adopting the current snapshot would silently rewrite history.","votes":[{"amendment_id":"fr-14-cb88579a","decision":"accept","rationale":"This correctly identifies a real defect: the implementation now explicitly avoids auto-populating plan_hash on new rows (`record_task_run_start` writes only caller-supplied plan_hash and stores the snapshot hash separately), while the accepted issue text and tests were supposed to require snapshot-based defaulting when callers omit it. Leaving the code and acceptance contract divergent is itself a maintainability and correctness problem. Either the contract must be changed or the code must be restored, so the amendment is valid."},{"amendment_id":"fr-14-793a2f7a","decision":"reject","rationale":"There is no remaining technical issue here. `StartJournalDetails` and `CompletionJournalDetails` already live in `src/contexts/milestone_record/model.rs`, are public, derive both `Serialize` and `Deserialize`, and are imported by `src/adapters/fs.rs` instead of being redefined there. The amendment mostly observes that the duplication was fixed elsewhere already, so it does not identify an actionable defect in the current code."},{"amendment_id":"fr-14-ab7143b0","decision":"accept","rationale":"Restoring snapshot-based defaulting on new running rows is technically merited. The current behavior drops plan_hash from fresh lineage rows, `BeadStarted` journal details, and in-flight reads even though the snapshot hash is already available at creation time, and later plan evolution can leave those attempts permanently unattributed. The claimed safety benefit is weak because the implementation still records `snapshot_plan_hash_at_creation` and later backfills from that same value when the snapshot stays unchanged; if that creation snapshot is trustworthy enough for deferred backfill, it should be written immediately. Reverting the tests that now assert `plan_hash == None` on start would catch the real regression instead of locking it in."},{"amendment_id":"fr-14-9bc460db","decision":"reject","rationale":"This goes too far for legacy rows with `snapshot_plan_hash_at_creation == None`. Those rows are genuinely ambiguous: they may predate any plan, or they may come from an older binary that failed to record provenance. Backfilling them from the current snapshot would silently relabel historical attempts with a plan version they may never have run under. Leaving some legacy entries unattributed is safer than writing false lineage; a broader repair would need additional provenance, not unconditional adoption of the current snapshot."}]}